	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Aug 28th 11:29 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[1.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Who came up with that "damage increase, not delay reduction"? Could you be a *bit* more confusing please? Haste makes the weapons swing faster. It does not make the weapon do more damage per swing. How much faster? The number of swings per minute is increased by the haste percent. It swings as fast as a weapon with lower delay, but there are two reasons that you can't think of haste as delay reduction:<br><br>1. There are bonuses based on the delay of the weapon, which isn't changed by haste (you still get the slow weapon bonus for a 40 delay weapon).<br><br>2. It doesn't stack as delay reduction. If you had a spell haste equiv to 20% delay reduction, and item haste equivalent to 20% deley reduction, this is not equivalent to 40% (additive) or 36% (multiplicative) delay reduction. It should be converted to 25% haste first (1 / 1.25 = 1 - .2), add those, to get 50% total haste, which gives 33% equivalent delay reduction.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
